instructions.en: Summary of the data relating to the creation and amendment of the record.

helptext.en:
The following guidelines are based on the National Council of Archives Rules for the Construction of Personal, Place and Corporate Names. 

Full Name

Use to record a concatenated form of the name. This can be useful for display or migration purposes but should not be used as a repalcement for the structured name data.

Title

In English only the titles Lord, Lady, Sir, Dame and Hon (Honourable) may precede the forename. However common practice allows for other titles, such as Mr, Mrs etc, to be used. Select the most appropriate.

Forename

A forename is the component of the name which a person is given in addition to his/her surname. All forenames, including middle names where known, should be listed to assist disambiguation between individuals.

Initials

These should only be used where the full name is not known or the individual is more usually known by their initials, eg. T.S. Eliot. 

Surname

The component of a name which a person usually shares with other members of their family.

Epithet

This is a word or phrase describing a person's status, position, occupation, nationality, place of birth etc. An epithet should be included as a qualifier where any confusion between persons may arise.

description.en: Describes the date, place of birth and parentage of an actor.Relates to the Actor resource model E21 via P98.

helptext.en:
Date of Birth

Where known give the full date of birth

Birthplace

Use to record the place where the person was, or is believed to have been, born.

Mother

Use to record the name of the biological mother. For step or adoptive parent relationships see HER Parentage.

Father

Use to record the name of the biological father. For step or adoptive parent relaitonship see HER Parentage.
